AB  - Important political events are known to influence political socialization anddevelopment (Green, Palmquist, and Schickler 2002). It is also possible thatsuch events impact political socialization within particular age cohorts, andalso across important social groups who may be impacted differently by landmarkevents. This paper examines whether landmark immigration events can leave apermanent mark on an individual's views toward immigrants and immigration, andwhether that impact varies across different ethnic/racial groups in the UnitedStates Specifically, we examine the cohort of individuals who were in theirformative years during the passage of major US immigration bills that wereproposed or enacted from 1965 to 2010. Altogether, we focus on four pieces oflandmark immigration legislation. The findings reveal variations on the effectof these events depending on the group in question; a relationship also emergesbetween these landmark legislative events and attitudes on immigration policies.The analysis contributes to an ongoing debate regarding the ways in whichpolitical elites influence attitudes, and we discuss how the findings may applyto other contexts outside the US.
